It took a week for all the substances to clear out of my system. Through the shaking, teeth chattering, sweat soaked sheets, I wished only for relief. "If I am meant to survive, please let me get through this night," I thought. "If I am meant to live, please let that begin now, and let me see why," I begged. 

The idea of feeling better physically made sense. Once the depressants and chemicals all exited me, my body would, hopefully, acclimate. It would start firing in ways that only seemed logical.

What I wasn't expecting were the changes I would experience mentally and emotionally.
Nearly every person in my life removed themselves at a time I needed them most. I don't blame them. What could they have done or said, really? I put myself in this hell. A hell they wouldn't be able to pull me out of, even if they knew how to. So I let them leave. I wished them well. I thanked them, apologized for the pain I had caused, and kissed them goodbye. For good.

And it was those two words that mattered most and shocked me. 
For good. 

I knew that room in my life was being made for new experiences, new places, and more love. I knew that certain people were seasons and that those seasons needed to end. 

The change I craved involved my spirit and my heart. 
And from the very second I was able to recognize how beautiful and precious this life is, I stopped seeing life as something that was happening to me, and started accepting that it was something perfectly happening for me. 
Be brave enough to believe. 

J. Raymond #jraymond #poetry #sobriety #recovery #keepgrowing

I realized this weekend that, over the course of 15+ years, I had developed a level of guilt that made it difficult to enjoy the things I love most in life. On Sunday afternoon, I was having a cup of coffee and reading a book on my recliner. Feet up, and with some Coltrane playing real smooth in the background. 

For me, this is bliss. 

Yet, I found myself losing concentration, having to go back and re-read paragraphs, scattered mentally. 
My mind was all over the place. Thinking about my workout from earlier - could I have done more? Thinking about this writing project I'm beginning - will it work out? 
My relationships. My schedule. 
Even when I last cleaned the goddam shower, or swept off the back porch. 

And suddenly, for the first time in over a decade, 
I STOPPED. 
I hit pause and realized I had constructed my own personal purgatory of sorts. Incapable of enjoying something I actually enjoy, because of guilt over things I'm not doing, have yet to do, or can't go back and do differently. 
I STOPPED. 
And I said to myself, "dude.... you're ALLOWED to enjoy this moment right here, shamelessly, and wholeheartedly. 
So I did. 
And I hope those of you who maybe inflict the same hells on yourself, find the clarity necessary to grant yourself a reprieve from the "should-be's". 
You deserve to enjoy life. Period. 
Much love, y'all. 
.

Depression is impartial. Non-judgmental. It cares not of status, stature, success, age, sex, denomination, or ethics.
It's ruthless and greedy.

Mine lies to me. 
Tells me that it's a good day to die. That my best isn't worthy of love. 
It uses every past traumatic experience as evidence. 
Masterfully painting the most horrific of futures. 
Worst case scenarios become probabilities. 
My depression tells me I won't be missed. 
That I'm a burden just by breathing, and the world wouldn't skip a beat without me. 
It's driven me mad. 
To addiction and self-medicating.
To isolate beneath waves of mania so looming and large that I begged for mercy. 
My depression convinces me that everyone will leave, that they should, and they'll be better off for it in the end. 
My depression hurts people I love before they have the chance to hurt me, because I deserve all the pain inflicted. 

My depression was wrong. 
Not a single lie spewed was true. 

I AM loved. 
I exude love. Even when I didn't see it, feel it, or was shown it....
I POSSESSED IT. HARNESSED IT. 
IT EXISTED WITHIN, MORE THAN I UNDERSTOOD. ENOUGH FOR ME. 
AND ENOUGH FOR YOU. 

So now I shine it excitedly in the same places I once waited anxiously for it to arrive. 
I don't wait anymore.
The greatest moments of my life haven't even happened yet. 
But amazing ones have! 
All this time, 
I thought the walls were closing and inching in, 
never realizing what was just on the other side of them. 
It breaks my heart to think about how close I truly was to ending it all,
and missing out on how beautiful life would eventually be. 
I didn't see it. 
I couldn't see it. 
I thought I was broken and ruined. Beyond repair. Someone doomed.
I thought I would never know peace. That happiness was something meant for other people. I thought my life was a point not worth proving. 

My depression lied to me. 
And so does yours. 
Our lives are worth living. 
Believe that.

Two years ago: addicted to drugs and alcohol, battling depression and anxiety, driving every person out of my life.......

Vs. 

TODAY. Clean. Sober. Productive. Positive. Loved. Happy. Content. Contributing. And....
at mother fucking PEACE! 

I swear to you, your entire life can change in an instant. The road leading to it will likely be long and painful. 
But, the second you decide enough is enough, and admit you need help, miracles start to take place. 
I was sick. Suicidal. Begging for acceptance and love from the wrong people. 
I was told once to stop playing the victim by the same person who was breaking my heart.
But you know what, she was right. 
It wasn't her fault for giving up or needing to move on without me. 
It was my fault for not letting go of what was no longer meant for me.
Resisting like that, because of fear, only keeps you from what's destined for you. Real love. The kind you don't need to beg for.
The very second I sought help, 
the entire world began to open up for me. 
I lost so many I once considered friends. And that made space for the most beautiful, healthy relationships I've ever had. 
Rock bottom is a perfect place to grow from, I found. 
It's ok to be afraid, to mourn the loss that comes with new growth. 
You'll have to shed dead weight. 
You'll have to forgive yourself, those who've hurt you, and step forward. 
I'll step with you, if you need help. 
Your life is worth living. 
Believe in that. 

J. Raymond #jraymond #sobriety #recovery

I had made peace with the fact that I was unwanted. That my heart would stay broken. And my home would remain an empty one for some time. 
Then you happened. You laid your hands on every broken and discarded piece of my heart and put it together so gently and carefully that I couldn't believe it. 
I still lose sleep thinking it's all some kind of dream. 
And you saw that too. You laid your hands on that, too.
And you showed me that there is a place and person meant for me. When I doubt myself, you reassure me. When I worry, you bring me peace. You. 

I swear, every single thing that's broke me down and left me for dead has led me to you. 
If there's a point to my life now, it begins and ends with you. 
Thank you, Denise. For being the kindest and most caring thing I've ever fucking known. 
I've waited my whole damn goddam life for us.

The biggest lies I've ever believed were my own. The ones I whispered to myself at my lowest and most alone. I'd dress them with lilies and ribbons and say "lower your expectations" or "it's all your fault anyway."

There were days wasted away wondering why everything I loved was so gutting.
"Love is excruciating and painful work,"
I'd tell myself. 
"Don't show them that your true colors are bloody and bruised." 
Hiding little bits and pieces of what made me me 
soon became a habit. 
Experience taught me that people ought not be trusted. 
They're thieves. 
Only feeding on what they were starved for, 
then fleeing once fed and satiated. 

It's taken me years to realize that the people who left me were never actually mine. That they were intended all along to bring me the gift of exposure. To shake awake the parts of myself dead asleep. To shine light into the forgotten dark corners of my heart. 
I'm shining now. 
And I'm grateful for every person who convinced themselves I wasn't something worth fighting for. 
It forced me to fight for myself. 
I'm fighting now. 
The greatest peace I've ever known I found on hells edges, 
where the only person willing to love me 
was me. 
I still struggle with the way people give up so easily. 
But I understand now that they deserve the same happiness I was pleading for. 
That I was never theirs either. 

The truth is, 
I was never asking for too much. 
My only mistake was thinking that I was somehow undeserving,
someone not enough. 
I will be loved. 
I will be love. 
I'm loving now. 

J. Raymond #jraymond

This is the twelfth time I'm moving 
in seven years.
I've lost count of the couches and floors in between. 
Like some sad vagrant,
never able to make a home anywhere
I once believed was meant for me. 

There's not much left to me now. 
I've little to my name. 
Where'd it all go, I wonder. 
All the records and books.
All the moments and time. 
Little bits of my story left behind, discarded or stolen. 
I thought there'd be more.
I've been so careless. 
I've been so reckless. 
But I'm doing it the right way 
these days. 
Running towards something, 
and not away from anything. 

I'm packing up what's left of my life and bringing it to you. 
All my bridges are burning down now. 
Please be careful with me. 
Please don't tire of me. 
Please see me for who I'm fighting like hell to be. 
Forgive my past,
I'm sorry for what we've been through. 
For every way we've been left. 
For every way we've fled. 
For every way we've bled.

All I ever wanted was to be enough for the few I grew close to. 
All I ever want now is to be enough for you. 
All I ever wanted was a place of our own, somewhere soft to land. 
All I ever want now is who I am
in your arms, here's the rest of my life
in your hands. 

J. Raymond #jraymond

To anyone alone today:

You're not. 
It's ok to feel that way, though. 
It'll pass. Listen to your favorite music. Watch those old movies. 
Find reasons to smile this season. Cook comfort food and savor it. 
Enjoy your own peace and quiet. 
Be witness to the beauty around you. There's so much of it, 
if we only remember to look. 
Reach out to those you miss most, 
if you can. 
If they're no longer around, 
remember the best of them and the times shared. 
Go for a walk. 
See the lights and speak to strangers. 
Extend a hand. Give them a moment.
Make them smile, and feel seen. 

Be present today, yet hold tight to the belief that better days are ahead. 
Take time to reflect on the blessings and lessons this year gifted you. 
Write them down. 
Close the doors you need to. 
Be intentional today. Aware. 
But please be gentle. 
Friendly and forgiving. 
It's ok to be sad. To cry, even. 
Even our most difficult times are precious and valuable. 
You are valuable. 
You are valued. 
Don't lose sight of the splendor around you. 
Don't lose hope. 
You are not alone. 
You are never, ever alone. 
If you don't hear it from anyone else,
Merry Christmas, Happy Holidays, I'm so excited for this New Year together, and thank you for being here with me.

It will all make sense. The pain will be worth it, and you'll be better for it in the end. 
The real work lies in the heartbreak. There's no growth where there's no resistance. Pay attention. 
Listen closely.....

I think it's psychotic to pretend that only happiness is the voice speaking to us. 
Sometimes, it's sadness. 
What's it saying? 
Sometimes, it's loneliness. 
What's it saying? 
Sometimes, it's doubt. 
What's it saying? 
Sometimes, it's fear. 
What's it saying? 

All the feelings are real. Very real. 
And they're telling us something. I no longer run from them. I don't numb out or uncouple myself from life anymore. I sit with them. I cry with them. I make a place for them at my table and hear them out. 

Once they've said their peace and are exhausted, they leave. And I laugh at myself for having made them so monstrous in my mind. 
Most fit nicely in my front pocket. Little stones are all they are. Meant to travel with me, proof of my humanness and resilience. They're not boulders rolling me over anymore. Just token reminders of everything I've survived. 

Walk with me. 
It will all make sense.

J. Raymond #jraymond

This last year, without question, has been the most challenging, heartbreaking and beautiful year of my life. It's brought me to my knees. It's broken me - my heart, and nearly my spirit. From moving three times across the country, watching my relationship come to an end, falling out of touch with nearly every friend I had left, squandering writing and work opportunities while battling a rapidly growing drug and alcohol addiction, until hitting my lowest of lows - FINALLY, I had hit rock bottom. I wanted to die. Literally. The morning after it all came "crashing down", I went to Google recovery centers and AA meetings, and the most recent search item was the phrase "how much alcohol does it take to kill yourself?".

And I really believed death was some welcomed reprieve. I was tired of hurting those I loved. I was tired of being hurt by them. I was, simply, tired of life. 

I say all of that, to say this - a year ago, had you said to me that I would be sober, clean, surrounded by the trees and mountains of Oregon, excited to wake up each day, and more in love than I'd ever been before, working to help other alcoholics find sobriety -
I would've thought you were more fucked up than me. 

The last 6 months of my life, since reaching that rock bottom, have been the most incredible months of my life. I truly didn't think this level of peace and optimism existed. I used to see happy people, and think they were faking it, or full of shit. Now, I'm one of those people, and it's so damn surreal. It breaks my heart to think about how close I actually came to taking my own life. To think back on how I treated those I cared deeply for. And how many years I've lost while battling with addictions and depression. I would go through them all again if it meant I could have the life I have today.

From the very second I let go of the things and people no longer for me, my life changed. In every facet. In the most amazing ways. My life today is unrecognizable compared to the one I had a year ago. 

If you're going through it, and you feel completely alone, and ending it like I felt...PLEASE KNOW THIS, 
IT GETS BETTER. Reach out to me. Get help. Don't quit. 
This is our year.
J

How did we get here, I wonder? Literally, to this day, in this space, as this person. 

It's nothing short of a miracle that I'm not dead or in jail. 
I used to say asinine things like, 
"I drive much better when I'm fucked up because it forces me to focus." 
Hurting myself was one thing. A wound to inflict upon myself as a way to feel and make a part of my story. 
But I didn't realize how much I was hurting others. How whoever was a part of my life was in very real danger simply by being near me. 

They say this addiction is a disease and that the word "disease" can be broken down to a feeling of "dis-ease." Today, every day, I wake up knowing it's still a part of me. That it's always inside, and lying in waiting.
Hoping I turn away from the light I've fought to find and face. 
Crossing my heart, hoping I die. 

But there's something else happening today, every day. Something I didn't know was there. Something rebuilt from heartbreak. Something shook loose and forged. Something I'm meant to share. 

Love. 
Hope. 
A horror story with a happy ending. 

Maybe it doesn't matter so much HOW we ended up here.
Only that we did. 
Maybe what matters now is what we make of what's left of our lives. 
That we take every single thing that sought to kill us, and instead
use it to save one another. 
For those who are still a part of my life, and all those who will someday be, please know this -
you will see how awesome you are, how strong and resilient you can be, 
simply by being near me.

Let it be said that I've earned every good thing in my life. That in spite of my mistakes, I survived. And though I've been treated poorly at times, I learned to thrive. None of what you see around and within me was gifted freely. 

I've never understood people who'd say the phrase "no regrets." How could that be? Was there something wrong with me for wishing I could go back and do a few things differently? I'd spare a few feelings, a few hearts, and be more kind to those I care for. Though I'm truly grateful for the life I have and the space I occupy, I've got a few wrongs I'm still hoping to right. Please, don't alter my course. 
Just..... I'm sorry.... 
that's what I'm trying to say. I'm trying to set loose the words I've choked back in fear and not care who's to blame anymore. I'll shoulder it. If that's what's needed for you and I to step out of this heavy night and into the warming light. 
Why the fuck are we so stubborn? Why can't we just be easier on one another? We allow these wounds to fester and spread. Little self-inflicted splinters serving as reminders of who's hurt us in the past. A pebble in our shoe that we refuse to shake out. A toothache that we can't wait to tell the world about. 

No. 
I'm no longer going to lie to myself and pretend the poison serves as fuel for my fire. I won't allow my many mistakes and disappointments to shape the person I am today. The person who was hurt and broken, or the person who hurt or broke you, is dead. I carry their regrets with me, and they no longer weigh me down. I'm a lot stronger now. 
It took a lot of suffering to become this content. It took a lot of breaking to become this whole. It took a lot of hardship to become this soft. 
In a world that tried to make me a lesser version of myself, let it be said, 
I became greater.

is so often placed in front of
“anxiety”
is because of the way it breaks your back.

lives in a home built atop worriment.

I will find tranquility.
I will make the space within myself
somewhere safe for you and I.
The next chord strum
will ring such certainty and collectedness
that our souls will know peace once more.

In time,
our backs will be strengthened,
our spines will straighten,

and we will stand once again,
a little taller than before.

One heavy step at a time.

Whether or not you're to blame. 
In the face of fear and shame.

only requires a willing heart and bravery.

Begin again.

It's not easy to share this....
Yesterday, I nearly said "fuck it". For no real reason in particular. 
7 months clean & sober almost wiped out over nothing. It was wildly unexpected. Came out of nowhere. I thought because I could be around others drinking and be where alcohol is being served and not be tempted whatsoever that I was somehow "cured" or had bested this beast. Nope. Yesterday I learned that the desire to hurt myself is strongest when nobody is around. Because hiding my drinking is what I've learned to do best. And when nobody is looking, I won't have to hide it. You won't have to see me sick and I can finally undress my shame privately. My pain obscured. My regrets can run amuck. I learned that all along, this disease was merely waiting, wanting me all to itself. I started telling myself nobody would know. Scared the shit out of me. I literally felt like "who cares", even after all the progress. I didn't think about the hundreds of people who message me every week about getting clean and sober. I didn't think about all the good shit that's happened since getting clean & sober. I thought, only, "it'll be different this time". I thought because I had gotten good at sobriety, I had gotten good at consuming. I didn't drink. But I still felt so guilty for having even considered it. When I went to my AA meeting that night, they all laughed and admitted that it sneaks up on them 10, 20, 30 years later. They'll be on an airplane, flying to Hawaii, and their brain will say "order a Bloody Mary, just one, you're on vacation and you've been sober for a long time". So, it's humbling to know that, once again, I'm not so utterly unique and helpless. I've got the same problem millions of others have. Yesterday, for the first time in my life, I didn't surrender to the thing that so badly wants to end it. I'm not sure why I'm afflicted and tortured with something so seemingly innocuous as a glass of Bourbon, but I am. I'm not alone. You're not alone. And though I've lost nearly every battle with myself over the years, yesterday, I won. Today, I arose less afraid, more alive, and a bit stronger than I've ever been before. So much love, y'all. 
J. Raymond #jraymond

I'll be honest with you, none of this is easy. Some nights, I dream of taking flight and never coming down. I awake those mornings in a panic, believing I actually started back up again. A part of me is still sick and stuck in a world on fire. 
A world I'm not actually in anymore. 

This isn't where I imagined myself. 
When I was a child, I wanted to be a professional baseball player. My father was my little league coach, and it was, without question, my favorite thing on earth. I'm named after him. Look just like him. Did you know that? 
No matter how much he drank, he never missed a game. He never made an excuse and asked someone to fill in for him, or lied his way out of it, or showed up late.......
or quit. 
I've quit so many good things. Jobs. Obligations. People who loved me. People who were counting on me. My friends and family. My son. Nearly myself, even. One of the lines I'd tell myself, when I most wanted to die, was that at least I'd get to see my pops again. Instead of writing about him all the time, I could finally look him in the face and tell him that I'm sorry, that I get it now, and I understand how he must've felt. I feel it, too. 
"Look, Dad, another thing we have in common! I have the same fucking problems. 
It won. I lost."

But no..... that isn't who he raised. Maybe his lesson all along wasn't that life would be insufferable, but that even at its most challenging, most painful, most helpless......you show up. 
You've just got to show up. 
Sometimes, you lose. Badly. 
Well, Dad... I showed up today. 
I quit the thing killing me today. 
I smiled and laughed and felt love today. 
I hope you're proud of your son, 
I wouldn't have made it without you. 
Today, I won.

The greatest revenge, I've come to learn, is becoming someone who no longer desires to exact it. 
Someone willing to break the endless cycle of painful reciprocation.
I can no longer afford to sacrifice myself trying to get even. 

I used to try like hell to hurt those who had broken my heart or spirit. An eye-for-an-eye, as I was taught. And when that didn't resonate or cut deeply enough, I would hurt myself. Believing that you would see what you drove me to be. That the guilt you should feel would bring you to your knees - right beside me. I so desperately wanted their remorse that it was paralyzing. 

I've wasted so much time mourning the loss of people who've left for me for dead, that I stopped creating a life for myself. Consumed with heartache and regret. I didn't realize that, no matter where I was, no matter how destitute or desperate, I could exude something far more beautiful. Nobody can force me into becoming a lesser version of myself, or drag me down into a world filled with spite. 

My hope for us is not that we strive to be altruistic but that we use our hardships as stepping stones forward. Onward. Upward. That we become an example of how love moves. We become someone who shows the world we refuse to wage war against others, and then become the peace often withheld from us. 
I've been fighting my whole goddam life for all the things that have existed in me all along. 
But I see now, the fight is over. 
I've already won.

Without faith, you're f*cked.
The hardest thing for me was finding it. The second hardest thing was keeping it. A great fact of life is that we all suffer. Every last one of us has endured heartbreak, struggle, misfortune, setbacks, and obstacles that the world is entirely and utterly unaware of.

When I say faith, I don't necessarily mean in a higher power. Some of us lose faith in our goals, our relationships, our health, and the most common of all - ourselves. I had lost faith in just about everything that once mattered in life. Getting out of bed felt pointless. In fact, if there weren't people around that I was trying to appease, I probably would have drank and drugged myself straight to hell. Alone. Quietly. My faith in anything good or positive was nonexistent. I lost faith in my passion. My heart. My ideas. My drive. And like many, once you lose faith, you don't simply stop trying - you start dying. 

Faith, itself, is the greatest initiator I know of. It's the beginning of everything. Without it, you're paralyzed. I found the faith I had lost at my absolute lowest and darkest. I can't tell you exactly why even. Mine felt like a miracle. A sparking of my spirit. An igniting of my heart. Suddenly, I was "cured" of this bottomless pit of addiction and depression. Almost as if the universe, or the creator, or an energy just reached down and f*cking spared me. Plucked me out of the place I was dying in and planted me somewhere overflowing with love, hope, and promise.....

Turns out, I'm still a fool. A grand idiot. Our work, our life's work, is in KEEPING OUR FAITH. Every day, I have to wake up and arm myself against my own thoughts. I have to actively shine a light on the things I'm grateful for, but too often overlook. See, as much as I love being alive today, it doesn't make it easier.  The challenges of life never stop. I'm grateful for that. I know now that nothing is a loss. Whatever is meant to be, will always be. Anything removed from my life, be it a person or opportunity, was never meant to stay in the first place. The relief and peace I know today hinges ENTIRELY on the faith I fight like hell to maintain. Fight with me! 

J. Raymond #jraymond

For what it’s worth,
 I would have waited on you forever.

More than anything else -
 you mattered.

And still,
the closer I moved towards you,
the more distant we grew.

What should one do

stops?

brush it off,
blame myself,
chase you down,
return what’s left,
and watch you set it back on the shelf?

The hardest part is that I deserve the discard.

But I need you to understand,
it’s not that I don’t want anybody else.
It’s that I can’t.
I see what's missing in everything.
And you were the one who used to ask me every day to be with you forever. 
I always said yes and meant it. 
Did you keep asking me, hoping you'd soon believe it? 
And that’s what keeps me weakly close by.
Eventually, I’ll have no choice but to forgive myself.
One of us must.
And I swear,
if I had to choose between us two,
I would rather it be you.

 It still feels as if the time I give to another
is being stolen from you.

Stubborn hearts have a hard time quitting.

 will never come true.

 For what it’s worth,

I want you to know it's going to be OK. 
You will heal from this. 
This won't kill you. You are not buried. You are not ruined. 
The relief you're looking for isn't disguised or hiding. 
It's only waiting. 
Moving on 
might begin with the slightest of movements. 
Blind faith is sometimes seen through swollen, tired eyes.
It's getting back up from heartache so great that it takes your breath away. 
It's one pant leg at a time when the seconds are standing still,
and going to that goddam restaurant by yourself. 
It's having to repeat yourself when they ask, "How many?".
It's rebuilding with whatever you still have left within. 
An exhausted spirit, but not one emptied. 

I want you to know you're not as alone as you believe. 
But this, this recovery, 
you have to do yourself. 
Inch by brutal inch. 
One heavy step at a time. 
You'll feel as if you're running in place, 
but I promise you, eventually, inevitably, 
you'll be amazed at how far you've come. 
Forgive yourself first. Completely. 
Whether or not you're to blame. 
In the face of fear and shame.
Even if you'll never be the same.

I want you to know it's going to be OK. That it's going to feel impossible to start over, from somewhere you never imagined you'd be. 
That where you're heading next 
only requires a willing heart and bravery. 
And that this moment, this very season you're in, 
is just that.....

a moment. This is not the end. 
Begin again.

J. Raymond #jraymond

Half.

62.

I truly had no idea that level of evil was so rampant. One of the many takeaways from this project, one which I wasn't expecting at the onset, is how much power there is in you sharing your story. Using your voices to rise up and make it very clear that you will not remain silent, you are survivors, you are proud, and you will turn something heinous into a story of strength. This is one of those stories from someone who was a victim of sexual assault and rape. Twice.

I hope I made you proud. I hope this connects.

I'm sorry for not using my platform to shine a brighter light on these issues.
I will do better.

Thank you for inspiring me, Leah.

Mostly,
we want to believe in someone
  who believes in us.
Trust takes tough times.
It asks you to make space,
 and welcome in something dangerous.
Something unpredictable.
Because everyone outside of ourselves,
 is a wavering variable.
A wild card
  filled with mismatching sets of circumstances.

We lay our cards face down
  in front of one another.
Turning them over anxiously.
Explaining the history of each,
 how we earned it.
 why we typically keep them close to our chest.
Secretly wondering
  if the other might have ones that match.

It’s rare when they do,
 but oh,
how magical it feels to be felt.
To be seen.
To be understood,
 at least,
 in some ways.
Similar suits and a pairing of hearts.
Even if only briefly,
 we’re set free.
And maybe what we’re really, truly
hoping for
is someone who sees us as a gamble
worth taking.
A bet,
 worth placing.

Someone who might see the differences,
 but finds life in our likeness.

The time between now 
and feeling your body against mine 
drags on painfully. 
So slowly it’s torturous. 
I waste days fantasizing every way 
you’ll respond to my touch. 
My mouth waters at the idea of us. 
You tease me with every sly smile. 
Every glance makes me shift in my seat. 
You lick your lips, and I melt. 
Everything about you is arousing. 
And I realize then 
that you know exactly what you’re doing. You’re toying with me. 
  Instigating me. 
  Baiting me. 

It’s working. 
What I’m feeling goes so far beyond lust. 
This is carnal. Something animalistic. Feral. Nobody has ever desired you more than I do, 
I promise you. 
I’m going to take my time. 
I want the taste of you on my tongue. 
Our fingers locked and pulling you in by your shoulders closer, deeper into me. 
This bed won’t contain us. 
Throw the sheets off. 
Beg for more. Arch your back. 
I want us on the floor. 
I know you need this as much as I do. 
I know the tension was rising in you 
just the same. 
I’m going to learn your every curve and the places that don’t get touched often enough. Let’s drown in each other. 
I want to watch you come down like rain. Completely full, 
until completely emptied. 
I’ll tell you when. 
I’ll let you know when it’s time.

Until then….

They say,
 “trust is something earned, not given”.

Though much of hers was stolen.
Leveraged against her,
 wrapped with ulterior motives.
I suppose after you’re fooled once,
 twice,
 and so on,

your faith in others is shaken.
Your view of the world
  forever misshapen.

But why do we place the blame 
on the most generous?
Why do we accuse the used of being foolish?

I hope she never changes.
I hope she fights against the bitter winds
  and never shuts down a heart
  both giving and open.
When you’re alone, you’re safe.
Unexposed, invulnerable,
 impenetrable.
But what made her beautiful were the very things
that made her susceptible.
How easy it would be to build defenses.
To climb in from out-on-that-limb
 and bury your treasures somewhere nobody would suspect.
What can’t be lifted
  can’t be reached.

Why do we allow the actions of others to determine
our treatment of another?

It's sick -
 the way the world takes advantage
  of those most benevolent.
She was one of the bravest people I’d ever know….
Not because of what she’d gone through,
 but the way she refused to be hardened by it.

Though she knew better than to believe and trust the world around her,
she knew nothing truer
  than the world within her.

I have to believe in our individuality,
I must.
I have to come face to face with my many faults
and flaws,
and remind myself, once again,
that you and I were never intended to be identical.

Give me lazy love. 
I used to fantasize over grand gestures 
and wild adventures. 
But the vast majority of our days together 
will be far simpler. 
Not spent sky diving and jet-setting. 
There’s nothing I enjoy more than slow, dawdling days spent in bed together, 
laughing, eating, making love in between episodes of some show we’re hardly watching. 

You’re my universe. 
Stunning without trying. 
You nestle further, sink deeper into me, 
as if you can’t get close enough. 
But I feel you in my bones. 
In my soul already. 
I feel your smile against my chest, 
and another little piece of me is made whole. 

I love knowing that you know 
you are safe with me. 
That’s not something either of us has had much of in the past. 
We breathe each other in, 
and our spirits exhale – finally, we’re at peace. Doing nothing whatsoever with you 
is my favorite thing to do. 
You make the mundane feel magical. Whatever extravagant dreams I once had for myself have been replaced by ones where you’re at the center of. 
A warm home filled with music, dancing, and all the things we love. 
I crave time together, making you smile, 
and showing you how much you are appreciated. 
I no longer crave the grandiose because with the right person, your person, 
all you need is their company 
for life to feel adventurous. 
We make fire from just the energy between us and the little corner of the world we share 
fills with purpose.

The last time we spoke, I meant to tell you that I think you’re incredible. 
But the words got stuck in my throat. 
You should know that I think of you all the time. You deserve to hear it said aloud, 
so I’m sorry for not saying what’s spilling out of my heart. 

Everything I do these days is with you in mind. I’ll walk by a beautiful home and imagine us inside one of our own. I hold off on trying new restaurants because I know I’ll enjoy them more with you. Postcards become places I envision us vacationing. 
I leave myself notes of questions to ask you, 
or things I found funny 
that I know you will, too. 
You’re the best, most beautiful part of my life. Woven into the fabric of my day. 
Sometimes, I talk myself out of telling you how proud of you I am. Kind words weren’t something I heard often growing up, so they still feel awkward and clumsy as they leave my lips. 
It’s easier for me to write them down. 
So, I hope these words land just the same. 
I hope you’re reading this in my voice and hear it how I do – I’m so proud of you, sweetheart. Life grows so hectic at times, 
and I’m sure you feel as if you’re spinning your wheels, wondering when it’ll get easier, or if all your hard work is worth it. 
I see the way you push yourself and how life sometimes pushes back. 
I see the way exhaustion shows up too early on long days. You look in the mirror and joke about how tired you look. 
But you should know that all I see 
is your strength. 
Your eyes look like home to me. 
All I see is the rest of my life. 
If you ever, 
for even one second, 
feel as if you’re not doing enough, 
please know that couldn’t be further from the truth. 
I’m sorry I didn’t say this earlier, 
when we spoke, 
but you are incredible. 
I'm here, 
whenever you need somewhere to rest. 
I'll remind you again then. 

J. Raymond

It’s funny, 
I once hated them for the way they left me. Now I just shake my head for staying so long. Time cuts in both directions, but the river only flows one way – forward. 
An ocean, washing lessons and people ashore. 
But you…
I would choose every version of you, 
in every lifetime. 
Over and over and over again. 

There were days I felt it was “too late” for me. Like I was destined to be left behind. 
Maybe my dreams had passed me by, 
the windows of opportunity 
all closed and locked tight. 
And other days 
I felt as if I had plenty of time, 
all of it in the world. 
So much I couldn’t hold it all. 
I’d watch as it slipped through my fingers, 
out of my hands. I rushed nothing. 
I ran nowhere. 

But I see now, it was all leading me here – 
to you. 
Every person was preparing me. 
Honing and tuning me just right. 
It’s funny, the way I believed they broke me. They convinced me I was ruined. Unlovable. Someone to pass through, 
never somewhere to grow roots. 
It’s so clear to me now – those not meant for us will never love us properly. 
I tried so hard to pull love 
from the wrong people. 
I tried to will myself into being who they needed me to be. 
I know better now than to fight for something that can’t be forced or coerced. 
All that pain was just the universe saying, 
“not this one”. 
I just wasn’t listening. 
It’s amazing that every single person who hurt me was only trying to bring me to you. 
I’m sorry it took me so long to be right on time.

I truly thought something was wrong with me before I met you. 
A few who didn’t mind twisting knives 
told me “Nobody will ever love you like I do”, until I soon believed it was romantic to bleed. Pain was the price you paid for passion. 
Every time I fell for another’s 
promise and touch, it took a little more 
to piece myself back together. 
You can only break in new ways 
so many times 
before you just stop trying. 
Before you learn the only person who can be trusted is yourself – 
and even that isn’t always so.

It's hard to believe that everything was a lesson in how to love myself better, for you.
I was becoming strong enough for us both.
Someone simply enough for us both.

Now, I can’t help but turn you into a poem. 
The way I hear songbirds in your laughter, 
and how you’re the only thing I’ve ever been addicted to that gives me life. 
You bring me sunlight.

Save yourself. Forgive yourself. Give yourself a fighting chance to live the life meant for you. 

I'm coming up on 16 months clean and sober. If you had told me 16 months ago that I would have the life I have today, living the way I am living, with the heart and spirit I carry with me now, I would not have believed you. Please believe me when I say this - you are not finished. You are not your addictions. You are not your depression. You are not your anxieties. You are not your heartache. You are not your illness. 

I know what it feels like to not want to be alive anymore. I truly do. But, if you just keep fighting, if you can be brave enough to make the changes and put in the real, hard work, life will transform into something so unbelievably beautiful that you'll think you're inside of dream. 

This book, The Kindred Project, changed my life at a time I was merely trying to hold on. I heard your stories, and they inspired my own. Thank you for connecting with my work, but more so, thank you for connecting with me - the flawed, wayward, wildly imperfect human being trying to be the best version of themselves. I'm not done growing yet. Nor are you. Let's grow and shine together. Let's give the world the magic inside of us that's just dying to be set free. I need it. We all need it. Let's start right now, from where we are, with everything we have left. You're loved. Know that. 

J. Raymond

All you have to do is be you, and I fall. 
Like dead weight. 
Only, this is the most alive I’ve ever been. Forgive me when I downplay the joy that I’m feeling. I don't mean to. 
That’s just my fear talking. 
That’s just old wounds whispering warnings. That’s just my knee-jerk response from a heart still healing. 

I say things like, 
“I know it won’t always be like this”, 
and you shrink into yourself. 
Your smile wilts like a dying rose that was full a moment ago. 
My pain swallows the sun, 
and I tell you I hate myself for projecting. 
Your kindness refuses to allow me to speak to myself that way, 
and I fall all over again. And again. 
And again. 
And I swear to you, I would go through another decade of wrought, hell, torment, and heartbreak, 
if I knew you were the reward waiting. 
You're my gift for not giving up when it’s the only thing that made sense. 
This is the greatest version I’ve ever been, 
and I’m still accepting myself, it seems. 
I’m not sure how you did it, 
but you laid your hands on all my broken parts and showed me they never actually were.

J. Raymond

To the 115 contributors who trusted me enough to turn their life stories into poetry, I am forever grateful. I began work on The Kindred Project at perhaps the most difficult time in my life. I was only a few weeks clean and sober, and connecting with you grounded me in the most beautiful ways. Ways that gave me strength and hope. The words you inspired have been read by hundreds of thousands of individuals from all around the world.

To those who signed up to be a part of Volume II, I'm so excited to work together. 

This has been the greatest year of my life, and please believe me when I say that your support, encouragement, kindness, and energy are the biggest reasons why. All I want to do with my life is create and connect, and because of you, I'm able to do that every day. 

So much love to you and yours. 
Thank you. For all of this. 

J. Raymond
